In `nth` methods, a sufficiently large `n` (combined with a non-zero internal index) could cause the addition to overflow and wrap around, producing a small "target index" that passed the bounds check and enabling reads at the front of the `list` or `tuple` of elements previously yielded by the iterator.

In `nth_back` methods, a sufficiently large `n` could cause underflow in a similar fashion, however would instead allow reads of arbitrary memory past the end of the `list` or `tuple` storage.", "ghsa_id": "GHSA-36hh-v3qg-5jq4", "github_reviewed_at": "2026-06-12T19:32:47Z", "html_url": "https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-36hh-v3qg-5jq4", "identifiers": [{"type": "GHSA", "value": "GHSA-36hh-v3qg-5jq4"}], "nvd_published_at": null, "published_at": "2026-06-12T19:32:47Z", "references": ["https://github.com/PyO3/pyo3/pull/6086", "https://rustsec.org/advisories/RUSTSEC-2026-0176.html", "https://github.com/advisories/GHSA-36hh-v3qg-5jq4"], "repository_advisory_url": null, "severity": "high", "source_code_location": "https://github.com/PyO3/pyo3", "summary": "PyO3 has an Out-of-bounds Read in `nth` / `nth_back` for `PyList` and `PyTuple` iterators", "type": "reviewed", "updated_at": "2026-06-12T19:32:49Z", "url": "https://api.github.com/advisories/GHSA-36hh-v3qg-5jq4", "vulnerabilities": [{"first_patched_version": "0.29.0", "package": {"ecosystem": "rust", "name": "pyo3"}, "vulnerable_functions": [], "vulnerable_version_range": "< 0.29.0"}], "withdrawn_at": null}
